\begin_layout Subsection*
Part (a)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}=7$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{*}=28$
\end_inset

.
 In turn, each firm produces 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}^{*}=q_{2}^{*}=14.$
\end_inset

 Profit for each firm at this price/quantity vector is equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\pi_{i}(p_{i}=7)=p^{*}\cdot q_{i}^{*}-C(q_{i}^{*})=7\cdot14-\frac{1}{2}\cdot14^{2}=0.\]

\end_inset

We need to check that this is an equilibrium.
 Consider a deviation by firm 1, such that it reduces its price to 
\begin_inset Formula $7-\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Then firm 1's payoff is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\pi_{1}(p_{1}=7-\varepsilon)=7\cdot28-\frac{1}{2}\cdot28^{2}<0.\]

\end_inset

The payoff from deviation is less than that from the candidate equilibrium
 price/quantity vector.
 The same applies for firm 2 and so this price/quantity vector constitutes
 an equilibrium.
\end_layout

